\begin_layout Section
Objective function
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Let 
\begin_inset Formula $p\in\rr^{3}$
\end_inset

 be the point at which we want to balance the object, 
\begin_inset Formula $\vec{n}$
\end_inset

 be its unit normal and 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{\text{com}}$
\end_inset

 the center of mass of the object.
 Then, if we define 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\vec{v}_{\text{com}}=\frac{p_{\text{com}}-p}{\abs{p_{\text{com}}-p}},
\]

\end_inset

we know the scene achieves true balance if 
\begin_inset Formula $\dprod{\vec{n}}{\vec{v}_{\text{com}}}\sim1$
\end_inset

.
 On the other hand, intuitive judgement seems to be better approximated
 by the center of mass of the convex hull of the object 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{\text{com\_ch}}$
\end_inset

.
 Therefore, if we let 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\vec{v}_{\text{com\_ch}}=\frac{p_{\text{com\_ch}}-p}{\abs{p_{\text{com\_ch}}-p}},
\]

\end_inset

then we would like 
\begin_inset Formula $\dprod{\vec{n}}{\vec{v}_{\text{com\_ch}}}$
\end_inset

 to be as far away as possible from 
\begin_inset Formula $1$
\end_inset

.
 Therefore, the first objective function we tried to minimize was 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
w_{2}\dprod{\vec{n}}{\vec{v}_{\text{com\_ch}}}-w_{1}\dprod{\vec{n}}{\vec{v}_{\text{com}}}.
\]

\end_inset

However, the distance from the centers of mass to the point also play an
 important role, so we changed this objective function to 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\boxed{\frac{w_{1}}{\abs{p_{\text{com}}-p}^{2}}\left(\dprod{\vec{n}}{\vec{v}_{\text{com}}}-1\right)^{2}+\frac{w_{2}}{\abs{p_{\text{com\_ch}}-p}^{2}}\left(\dprod{\vec{n}}{\vec{v}_{\text{com\_ch}}}+1\right)^{2}}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Section
Changing the density of a given region
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Remember that a region 
\begin_inset Formula $B\subset\rr^{3}$
\end_inset

 inside 3D space has center of mass
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\com B=\frac{1}{\mass B}\int_{B}\vec{p}\,d\rho(\vec{p})=\frac{1}{\mass B}\left(\int_{B}x\,d\rho(\vec{p}),\int_{B}y\,d\rho(\vec{p}),\int_{B}z\,d\rho(\vec{p})\right)
\]

\end_inset

where 
\begin_inset Formula $\vec{p}=(x,y,z)$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho(\vec{p})$
\end_inset

 represents the density at point 
\begin_inset Formula $\vec{p}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\mass B=\int_{B}d\rho(\vec{p})$
\end_inset

 is the total mass.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Notation*
Given a region 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

 in 3D space, keeping into account a density function 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho$
\end_inset

, its center of mass will be denoted 
\begin_inset Formula $\com B$
\end_inset

.
 When the density is assumed to be constant equal to 
\begin_inset Formula $1$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho\equiv1$
\end_inset

, it will be denoted 
\begin_inset Formula $\comc B$
\end_inset

.
 The same goes for 
\begin_inset Formula $\mass B$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\massc B$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Now consider a especial region 
\begin_inset Formula $R\subset B$
\end_inset

 inside the body and consider the density
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\rho(\vec{p})=\begin{cases}
\alpha & \text{if }\vec{p}\in R\\
1 & \text{if }\vec{p}\in B\setminus R
\end{cases}.
\]

\end_inset

Then 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\begin{aligned}\mass B\com B & =\int_{B}\vec{p}\,d\rho(\vec{p})=\alpha\int_{R}\vec{p}\,d\vec{p}+\int_{B\setminus R}\vec{p}\,d\vec{p}\\
 & =(\alpha-1)\int_{R}\vec{p}\,d\vec{p}+\int_{B}\vec{p}\,d\vec{p}\\
 & =(\alpha-1)\vol R\comc R+\vol B\comc B.
\end{aligned}
\]

\end_inset

So, using 
\begin_inset Formula $\mass B=\alpha\vol R+\vol{B\setminus R}=(\alpha-1)\vol R+\vol B$
\end_inset

 we deduce
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\com B=\frac{(\alpha-1)\vol R}{(\alpha-1)\vol R+\vol B}\cdot\comc R+\frac{\vol B}{(\alpha-1)\vol R+\vol B}\cdot\comc B
\]

\end_inset

which can be rewritten as
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\boxed{\com B=(1-\theta)\cdot\comc R+\theta\cdot\comc B,\quad\theta:=\frac{\vol B}{(\alpha-1)\vol R+\vol B}}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Case
The especial case where 
\begin_inset Formula $R\subset B$
\end_inset

 is a hollow region of the body (i.e.
 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha=0$
\end_inset

) we get 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\boxed{\com B=(1-\theta)\cdot\comc R+\theta\cdot\comc B,\quad\theta:=\frac{\vol B}{\vol B-\vol R}}
\]

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Case
If we use ABS material with a metal ball on the inside then we get 
\begin_inset Formula $\a\approx8$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula 
\[
\theta\frac{\vol B}{(\alpha-1)\vol R+\vol B}=\frac{1}{C\frac{r^{3}}{\vol B}+1}.
\]

\end_inset

Theta decreases A LOT the more we can increase 
\begin_inset Formula $r$
\end_inset

.
 Therefore, the bigger the ball, the more the COM moves.
\end_layout

